### Instruction
- **To open an app, use Launch(app='app_name') as the first attempt.**
  If a previous Launch for the same app left the device on the home screen and the app icon is visible, do not call Launch again.
  Tap the visible app icon, or use the app drawer/search, so the run can make forward progress.
  Only keep using Launch when the previous Launch actually changed the screen or the app icon is not visible.
- **Choose the installation path from the user's input.**
  If the task provides a direct APK/download URL or local APK path, use InstallApk(source='...') before launching the app.
  Do not open Play Store, Chrome, or a Google account verification flow to install an APK from a direct package link.
  If the task provides a store/deep link that is not a direct APK package, use OpenLink(url='...') and follow the installer or store UI.
  If no installable link is provided, try the device app store first: Launch(app='play store'), search for the requested app,
  and install it from there. If no app store or installer is available, report the blocker clearly.
  If the task asks to remove the app, use Uninstall(app='app_name') instead of navigating through Settings.
- **Give up early on irrecoverable install failures.**
  If the task requires installing an APK and the install fails in a way you cannot fix
  (parse error dialog such as "There was a problem parsing the package", install denied,
  incompatible APK, corrupted download, etc.), do NOT keep retrying or dismissing the dialog.
  Call Finished(verdict='blocker', content='...') immediately and use the content to clearly
  describe the blocker (which APK, what error message you observed). The same applies if you
  can see that a required upstream step is irrecoverably broken.
- **Choose the right verdict when you call Finished.**
  Finished takes a `verdict` argument with three possible values:
  * `verdict='pass'` (default) — the task's success criteria are fully met. Use `content` for
    a short summary of what was accomplished.
  * `verdict='bug'` — you ran the task and the application under test did NOT behave as the
    task required (assertion failed, expected screen never appeared, expected content was
    wrong, etc.). Use `content` to describe **what was expected vs what you observed**.
    This signals a product defect.
  * `verdict='blocker'` — the test could not be completed because of an environmental or
    setup issue that is NOT a defect in the app under test (APK install failed, account
    sign-in unavailable, network down, missing precondition, device error, etc.).
    Use `content` to clearly describe the blocker.
  Pick the verdict deliberately: `pass` for a successful test, `bug` only for verified
  misbehavior of the product, `blocker` for everything else that prevents reaching a verdict.
- Always accept permission/privacy screens not part of the task.
- **Use the Current Progress and Current Step Goal** to understand where you are in the task.
  Do NOT repeat steps that are already marked as completed in the progress.
- If the user task naturally has multiple parts, emit `<current_step>` ONLY on the turn that
  starts work on a new part. Use a short phrase, ideally taken verbatim from the user query.
  Omit the tag entirely while continuing the same part — the runner remembers the last value.
- **If the Last Action Reflection indicates a failure**, address the suggested fix rather than
  blindly retrying the same action.
- If the task includes a "Private execution inputs" section, use those exact values when typing account identifiers,
  passwords, or verification data. Do not type placeholder descriptions such as "[provided email]".
- **Scroll Logic**: Always follow the physical swipe rule. To move the viewport to the RIGHT, your finger must move LEFT (start_x > end_x).
- Make sure you understand the task goal to avoid wrong actions.
- Make sure you carefully examine the the current screenshot. Sometimes the summarized
  history might not be reliable, over-claiming some effects.
- Consider exploring the screen by using the 'scroll' action with different directions to reveal
  additional content.
- To copy some text: first select the exact text you want to copy, which usually also brings up
  the text selection bar, then click the 'copy' button in bar.
- To paste text into a text box, first long press the text box, then usually the text selection bar
  will appear with a 'paste' button in it.
